Age and BMI in Down Syndrome

2022 April 14

Overview of this R Markdown File

This R Markdown file contains 3 tables and 1 figure that can be used in the age and BMI in Down syndrome study. The tables include age, gender, anthropometrics, premorbid ID level, diagnosis, karyotype, cognitive scores from the mental state exam and cued recall, and Alzheimers disease markers. The first table is stratified by diagnosis and the second table is stratified by age category. Frequency (percentage) is reported for categorical variables and mean standard deviation is reported for continuous measures. Overall sample size is 265 adults with Down syndrome unless indicated otherwise in the footnote.



Table 1. Anthropometrics, Alzheimers disease markers, and cognitive scores by diagnosis


Table 2. Anthropometrics, Alzheimers disease markers, and cognitive scores by age groups



Analysis


For this analysis, linear and polynomial regressions for the effect of age on 5 outcome variables (BMI, Centiloid AB, Tau, Mental State Exam, and Cued Recall) were evaluated. First, the adjusted R Squared for the crude effect of age on each outcome variable was compared using linear regression and polynomial regressions up to a degree of 5. The highest adjusted R squared defined the starting model. After the type of model (linear or polynomial) and degree (1-5) were determined, a forward stepwise regression was used to determine the final models. Covariates (i.e., gender, race, ethnicity, diagnosis, premorbid id level, karyotype, and APOE4) were added to the models one at a time and kept in the model if they increased the adjusted R squared, did not reduce the sample size by more than 50 observations, and either were significant (p < 0.05) in the model or altered any of the age coefficients by more than 5%. The final model was determined using the highest adjusted R squared values from the forward stepwise regressions.


Table 3. Polynomial Regressions for the effect of age on BMI, Centiloid AB, Tau, Mental State Exam, and Cued Recall


Final Adjusted R-Squared Values were 0.1231 (BMI), 0.6243 (Centiloid AB), 0.6104 (Tau), 0.5457 (Mental State Exam), and 0.5766 (Cued Recall)


Figure 1. The effect of age on scaled Alzheimers disease markers in adults with Down syndrome using polynomial regressions

Figure 1 plots the crude effect of age on each of the 5 outcome variables (BMI, Centiloid AB, Tau, Mental State Exam, and Cued Recall). Each line on the plot represents the polynomial regression fit to the degree that had the highest adjusted R-squared values. This was degree 2 for Centiloid AB, 3 for BMI and Cued Recall, and 4 for Tau and Mental State Exam. Each outcome variable is centered (subtracted from the mean) and scaled (divided by the standard deviation) to be able to add the variables to the same plot. The y-axis is in standard deviation units with 3 SD units on either side of the mean. An estimation of Prodromoal Alzheimers disease is displayed on the x-axis.
